<subSubSection id="16BFC059EE464B89BB9ABF34F45D3EDC" lastPageId="81" lastPageNumber="82" pageId="80" pageNumber="81" type="description">
<paragraph id="A225969F23B7BA53825945614381A424" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C7F888180645830D7B30C04D9C22500C" lastPageId="81" lastPageNumber="82" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">
Prostrate perennial herb, densely tomentose on all vegetative parts, often brownish when dry. Leaves petiolate, 1.2-5 
<normalizedToken id="0C400DCFD8A33F6A0CD9195E14AB59E7" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5-2.5 cm, variable in shape, ovate, lanceolate-deltoid or, most commonly oblong, margin undulate to crenate, base hastate to sagittate; petioles 3-6 (-20) mm. Flowers solitary, axillary, pedunculate; peduncles solitary or, occasionally, paired, 1.5-4 cm, often arching; bracteoles 5-7 
<pageBreakToken id="62D67901A0444FBE56B6BD1526DCA66D" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" start="start">mm</pageBreakToken>
, linear; pedicels 3-8 (-15) mm; outer sepals 9-11 
<normalizedToken id="152DACAAC1B2C60D10718AC4EBB5D913" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5 mm, ovate, acute to shortly acuminate, densely hairy; corolla (1.3-)1.5-1.8 cm long, white, unlobed, midpetaline bands pubescent, terminating in a tooth; ovary glabrous. Capsule glabrous; seeds glabrous, nearly smooth but somewhat rugose on the angles. [
<bibRefCitation id="B4F8FE276141865A999CF175EF07D20A" author="Verdcourt, B" editor="Hubbard, CE" journalOrPublisher="HMSO, London" pageId="213" pageNumber="214" pagination="1 - 161" refId="B373" refString="Verdcourt, B, 1963. Convolvulaceae. In: Hubbard, CE, Milne-Redhead, E, Eds., Flora of Tropical East Africa. HMSO, London: 1 - 161" title="Convolvulaceae." volumeTitle="Flora of Tropical East Africa." year="1963">Verdcourt 1963</bibRefCitation>
: 42 (as 
<taxonomicName id="E15785E75218D34D4A041D4A29130990" authorityName="Schulze-Menz" authorityYear="1939" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus zernyi" order="Solanales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="zernyi">
<emphasis id="3DB323496ABB5DB9B6D8DB6D1A1B80CD" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Convolvulus zernyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
)]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8E6C5463BF51A1D17B425A9BAED6568B" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BEE102DE3B5B98CE1D3D9C444665ABE" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4C770781822216E80DD1D2A77F2152DA" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
Malawi (
<emphasis id="DD360DF780536A09596E4930658DB368" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Synge</emphasis>
WC 251, 
<emphasis id="D7A2DC341B79EBDA699BD5C617CAEA79" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Pawek</emphasis>
13111, 
<emphasis id="0652A389A119F178EC5DA88E3A1C3BCA" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Richards</emphasis>
20646); Tanzania (
<emphasis id="DA720412FA302D0257C3DED145A0B3B5" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Lovett et al.</emphasis>
2089, 
<emphasis id="7FCD816CF4E37FF72474BD2DED73FCA5" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Mgaza</emphasis>
121). 1800-2100 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="699C4943BF39EC6D8F384C85710EE01C" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" type="notes">
<paragraph id="868D7E45139FC3C64501EACC6697A16C" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E6A741442E3EAAB37D579C1C42672DAD" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
We have widened the concept of this species from that of 
<bibRefCitation id="82196193C05D6BA7EF274BCAA31251A4" author="Verdcourt, B" editor="Hubbard, CE" journalOrPublisher="HMSO, London" pageId="213" pageNumber="214" pagination="1 - 161" refId="B373" refString="Verdcourt, B, 1963. Convolvulaceae. In: Hubbard, CE, Milne-Redhead, E, Eds., Flora of Tropical East Africa. HMSO, London: 1 - 161" title="Convolvulaceae." volumeTitle="Flora of Tropical East Africa." year="1963">Verdcourt (1963)</bibRefCitation>
to include plants with a somewhat smaller corolla and calyx, including the type of 
<taxonomicName id="B0D1161E0B033A0EE88F7853C7B9D44F" authorityName="Baker, Bull Misc. Inform. Kew 1894: 67. 1894. (Baker" authorityYear="1894" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus thomsonii" order="Solanales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="thomsonii">
<emphasis id="FC04F4DEBD5EDA17BC53B853339BC399" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Convolvulus thomsonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is atypical in its relatively short calyx and corolla but is clearly an immature specimen of this taxon. This species appears to be frequent in the highlands of northern Malawi and southern Tanzania. It is very close to 
<taxonomicName id="4F2B3B0DE96247A5361AE51FC70B0D91" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus sagittatus" order="Solanales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagittatus">
<emphasis id="2958FEA8113F00F3049DF6B9A531B8F1" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Convolvulus sagittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs in the larger sepals, 9-11 mm in length and the tomentose indumentum, which dries brown. The rather long, often arching peduncles are also very characteristic. An unusual feature is the occasional presence of paired peduncles. It can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="CA3767151841677700CBC3B1BCDCD83D" authorityName="Engl., Abh. Koenigl. Akad. Wiss. Berlin 2: 349. 1892. (Engler" authorityYear="1892" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus aschersonii" order="Solanales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aschersonii">
<emphasis id="8B63D51FBD812744F0D01077E1335038" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Convolvulus aschersonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="E2CCBB0826872EDEF2B06483AC64B7C2" authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus austroafricanus" order="Solanales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="austroafricanus">
<emphasis id="F8A6CB2973D34710E13F5DB0FA8EFED5" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Convolvulus austroafricanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the larger solitary flowers as well as the tomentose indumentum. It is also close to 
<taxonomicName id="2CB628560F855583C092926CB8E59371" authorityName="C. H. Wright, Fl. Cap. (Harvey) 4 (2): 75. 1904. (Baker and Wright" authorityYear="1904" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus galpinii" order="Solanales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="galpinii">
<emphasis id="62D13A9D45B71CB8216A0714B697BDB6" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Convolvulus galpinii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differing principally in the longer, gradually narrowed sepals.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D631B3CCDE400A932C90640960F24C8D" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
As with many other African species, intermediates with other species are found. These have the same indumentum, relatively large corollas and sepals of 
<taxonomicName id="86130BBB4CA55FB015D19547F3B3F3C9" authorityName="Baker, Bull Misc. Inform. Kew 1894: 67. 1894. (Baker" authorityYear="1894" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus thomsonii" order="Solanales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="thomsonii">
<emphasis id="CA6147D22AF9B22EAEC5CC0BD3CE66F3" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Convolvulus thomsonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but inflorescences of 2-3 flowers. 
<emphasis id="E98D5D814609ACABE6F77A3323DCB7C6" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Phillips</emphasis>
2738 and 3920 from northern Malawi and 
<emphasis id="64E572599B392E5CDFBB3F7EA09A57C2" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Richards</emphasis>
6071 from Zambia appear to be intermediate with 
<taxonomicName id="72888D4928F39EAB71EEBFC6F4F0D10E" authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus austroafricanus" order="Solanales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="austroafricanus">
<emphasis id="5EE3FD206ADBB7678AA4754C4D2ECF3F" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Convolvulus austroafricanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or possibly 
<taxonomicName id="0233807AB6EEEDD0A87EBC63E6478AF8" authorityName="Engl., Abh. Koenigl. Akad. Wiss. Berlin 2: 349. 1892. (Engler" authorityYear="1892" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus aschersonii" order="Solanales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aschersonii">
<emphasis id="719A9D1C50C6B42C851550C4932E9D19" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Convolvulus aschersonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
